<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3AF70AC4-19B0-4B79-8A06-D63F374FC0E7"><gtr:id>3AF70AC4-19B0-4B79-8A06-D63F374FC0E7</gtr:id><gtr:name>Queen Margaret University Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:department>Clinical Audiology Speech &amp;Lang Res Cen</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Queen Margaret University Drive</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Musselburgh</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH21 6UU</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3AF70AC4-19B0-4B79-8A06-D63F374FC0E7"><gtr:id>3AF70AC4-19B0-4B79-8A06-D63F374FC0E7</gtr:id><gtr:name>Queen Margaret University Edinburgh</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Queen Margaret University Drive</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Musselburgh</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Edinburgh</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>EH21 6UU</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>Scotland</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8B861C29-013E-4E01-AD7F-643E9E413D85"><gtr:id>8B861C29-013E-4E01-AD7F-643E9E413D85</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Sonja</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Schaeffler</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE012272%2F1"><gtr:id>3ABCA40E-9053-4B0C-9B17-B0C2AD5A14AA</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Phonetic Details of Speech Variation and Their Impact on Listener Comprehension and Attention</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E012272/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>The over-arching theme for the research carried out throughout the postdoctoral year is the analysis of the phonetic details of speech variation and their impact on listener perception.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Part of the postdoctoral year will be spent on a comprehensive analysis of the interplay of speaker affect, phonetic variation, listener perception&amp;nbsp; and comprehension ? based on data collected during the researcher?s previous PhD project. Results will be disseminated at conferences and in a submission to a peer-reviewed journal.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The other part of the postdoctoral year will focus on a new aspect of&amp;nbsp; fine-phonetic variation, namely the deviation of second-language learners and bilinguals from mono-lingual patterns, and its impact on perceived nativeness. An interesting concept that might be able to capture language-specific phonetic detail and allow for comparisons between native and non-native speakers is that of&amp;nbsp; ?articulatory settings?. As there is little empirical evidence for this concept so far the aim of the current project will be to draw up a methodology apt to investigate articulatory settings in future projects. To this end a small amount of pilot data will be gathered using Eletropalatography. Results of this pilot study will serve as a basis for future research and inform applications for further funding.
&lt;br />&amp;nbsp;
